	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>MottZilla</b> [ Sun Oct 19, 2008 10:40 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Fx3 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I just hook any subroutine calls for disk access like LoadFiles() and execute the same thing in C++ code. It beats emulating the actual drive. :p And it loads instantly which is nice.</div><br /><br />How do you handle the other registers, like 402x and 403x?</div>
<br />
<br />I return certain values for certain registers the bios and games may check so it passes through. Really by always returning certain values and hooking subroutines like the LoadFiles() you can get most games running very easily. The hard part is writing all the code to execute each function you want. LoadFiles() is the only one really needed. If you intercept calls to it, the only other thing you need to do would be intercept calls to some other routines so they don't fail but you don't actually have to add them in. 
<br />
<br />I'm just speaking from my experience with my emulator.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
